We study calibration and calibeating under general proper scoring rules.
Existing adversarial guarantees are stated for the quadratic (Brier)
scoring rule. We ask whether they persist when the evaluator uses an
arbitrary proper scoring rule. We restrict attention to proper Lipschitz
scoring rules and define the corresponding notions of
proper-calibration and proper-calibeating, uniformly over all proper
$1$-Lipschitz scoring rules.

Our first result is that calibration transfers for free: every
$\varepsilon$-calibrated procedure is automatically
$\varepsilon$-proper-calibrated, and every continuously
$\varepsilon$-calibrated procedure is continuously
$\varepsilon$-proper-calibrated. In contrast, calibeating does not
transfer: we exhibit a calibrated forecasting sequence that calibeats a
reference forecaster under the Brier score but fails to do so under a
proper Lipschitz scoring rule.

We then provide three routes to proper calibeating. First, the simple
deterministic procedure of Foster and Hart (2023), which forecasts the
running average action in the reference forecaster's bin, is in fact
proper-calibeating. Second, a stochastic procedure that calibeats the
joint binning is both proper-calibeating and proper-calibrated. Third,
there exists a deterministic continuously proper-calibrated procedure
that proper-calibeats. The key technical tool for the continuous result
is an approximate decomposition of the score into calibration and
refinement terms for $\delta$-local fractional binnings. All these
results extend to simultaneous proper-calibeating of multiple reference
forecasters.
